Understanding Financial Trends Visualization¶

This interactive visualization illustrates financial trends over time based on different expenditure categories.

How to Use:¶

  1. Selecting Categories:

    • Click on the legend to highlight or isolate specific spending categories.

  2. Exploring Trends:

    • Hover over the lines to view details about each category's expenditure, including the category name, the date, and the total expenditure for that month.

  3. Navigating Time:

    • Use the x-axis (date axis) to explore financial trends over different time periods.

Insights:¶

  • Color Legend: Each color represents a specific spending category.
  • Interactivity: Click, hover, and explore! Use the legend and hover over the lines to dive deeper into each category's financial trend.

Tips:¶

  • Category Selection: Click on a category in the legend to focus on its trend or compare multiple categories.
  • Time Period: Use the x-axis slider to view financial trends across different timeframes.

Enjoy exploring financial trends and gaining insights into expenditure patterns over time!

# Convert 'Record Date' to datetime 
df['Record Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Record Date'])

# Group by 'Classification Description' and calculate the sum of amounts for each description over all time
grouped = df.groupby('Classification Description')['Current Month Receipt or Outlay Amount'].sum().reset_index()

# Find the top 10 classifications based on total amount over all time
top_10_all_time = grouped.nlargest(10, 'Current Month Receipt or Outlay Amount')

# Filter the original DataFrame for the top 10 classifications
filtered_df = df[df['Classification Description'].isin(top_10_all_time['Classification Description'])]

# Altair plot to visualize the top 10 classifications over time
selection = alt.selection_single(fields=['Classification Description'], empty='all')
color = alt.condition(selection, alt.Color('Classification Description:N', legend=None), alt.value('lightgray'))

chart = alt.Chart(filtered_df).mark_line().encode(
    x='Record Date:T',
    y='Current Month Receipt or Outlay Amount:Q',
    color=color,
    tooltip=['Classification Description:N', 'Record Date:T', 'Current Month Receipt or Outlay Amount:Q']
).add_selection(selection)

# Add circles for each data point
circles = chart.mark_circle().encode(
    x='Record Date:T',
    y='Current Month Receipt or Outlay Amount:Q',
    color=color
).transform_filter(selection)

chart = chart + circles

chart = chart.properties(
    width=800,
    height=400,
    title='Top 10 Classification Descriptions over Time for All Time'
).interactive()

Financial Trends Interactive Visualization¶

This visualization allows users to explore financial trends over different expenditure categories across various time periods.

How to Use:¶

  1. Selecting Categories:

    • Use the dropdown menu to choose one or multiple expenditure categories. Hold 'Ctrl' for multiple selections.

  2. Exploring Trends:

    • Adjust the year range slider to view financial trends within specific periods.

  3. Navigating Interaction:

    • Click on a category in the dropdown to focus on its trend or compare multiple categories simultaneously.

Insights:¶

  • Visualization Details: The plot illustrates financial trends for the selected expenditure categories.
  • Color Legend: Each line color represents a different expenditure category.
  • Interaction Tips: Hold 'Ctrl' for multiple selections and adjust the year range slider to explore different timeframes.

Plot Details:¶

  • X-Axis: Represents the 'Record Date', indicating time.
  • Y-Axis: Displays total expenditure amounts in billions (formatted in millions for values less than a billion).

Enjoy exploring and analyzing financial trends across different expenditure categories and timeframes!

# Group by 'Classification Description' and calculate the sum of amounts for each description over time
grouped = df.groupby(['Classification Description', 'Record Date'])['Current Month Receipt or Outlay Amount'].sum()

# Find all classifications based on total amount
all_classifications = grouped.groupby('Classification Description').sum().index

# Create a dictionary to store data for all classifications
data_dict = {classification: grouped[classification] for classification in all_classifications}

# Function to convert y-axis labels to billions in dollars
def convert_to_millions(amount, pos):
        return f'${amount / 1e6:.1f}M'

# Create interactive plot based on a range of years and classification description
@widgets.interact(year_range=widgets.IntRangeSlider(value=[df['Record Date'].dt.year.min(), 
                                                         df['Record Date'].dt.year.max()], 
                                                    min=df['Record Date'].dt.year.min(), 
                                                    max=df['Record Date'].dt.year.max(),
                                                    description='Year Range'),
                  classification=widgets.SelectMultiple(options=all_classifications, description='Classification'),
                  instructions=widgets.Label(value='Hold Ctrl for multiple selections'))
def plot_data(year_range, classification, instructions):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    
    for classif in classification:
        filtered_data = data_dict[classif][(data_dict[classif].index.get_level_values('Record Date').year >= year_range[0]) &
                                           (data_dict[classif].index.get_level_values('Record Date').year <= year_range[1])]
        plt.plot(filtered_data.index.get_level_values('Record Date'), filtered_data.values, marker='o', linestyle='-', label=classif)
    
    plt.title(f'Trends between {year_range[0]} and {year_range[1]}')
    plt.xlabel('Record Date')
    plt.ylabel('Total Amount (in Billions)')
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.gca().yaxis.set_major_formatter(plt.FuncFormatter(convert_to_millions))  # Apply the formatter
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

#See how the Currrent Year Budget Estimates as changed over the last 5 years
# Set the style of seaborn
sns.set(style="whitegrid")
# Filter the data for the last 5 years
last_5_years = statement[statement['Fiscal Year'].between(statement['Fiscal Year'].max() - 4, statement['Fiscal Year'].max())]

# Group by 'Fiscal Year' and calculate the sum of 'Current Year Budget Estimate Amount' for each year
BudgetEstimate= last_5_years.groupby('Fiscal Year')['Current Year Budget Estimate Amount'].sum()

# Function to format y-axis labels as millions
def format_millions(value, _):
    return "${:.2f}M".format(value / 1e8)
# Formatting y-axis labels as billions
plt.gca().yaxis.set_major_formatter(FuncFormatter(format_millions))

# Plotting a bar chart
plt.bar(BudgetEstimate.index, BudgetEstimate.values, color='skyblue')
plt.xlabel('Fiscal Year')
plt.ylabel('Current Year Budget Estimate Amount')
plt.title('Current Year Budget Estimates Over the Last 5 Years')
plt.show()
plt.savefig('Current Year Budget Estimates Over the Last 5 Years.png')

<Figure size 1500x1000 with 0 Axes>

The final graph shows the expenditure of all three departments. We can see that the Department of Defense has spent the most in the most months across five years: from October 2018 to October 2023. There is a spike in spending by the Department of Education towards the end of 2022 and a plunge in around September of 2023. There is also a spike in Health and Human Services spending around the beginning of 2020 which can be explained by the beginning of the COVID-19 pandemic when the government allocated resources towards addressing the damage caused by the pandemic, including payments to individuals provided by CARES Act and other expenditures.
